I’d like to talk about an environmental problem that people in Vietnam are currently facing, which is air pollution. Although it is a global issue, it has become particularly serious in developing countries like Vietnam.

The main causes of air pollution include emissions from factories, heavy traffic, and the continued use of coal for power generation. In large cities, especially during rush hours, the air quality can drop significantly due to the high number of motorbikes and cars on the road.

This problem has serious consequences for both public health and the environment. People who are exposed to polluted air over a long period are more likely to suffer from respiratory illnesses, lung cancer, and cardiovascular diseases. It also reduces overall quality of life and can even affect economic productivity.

To tackle this issue, I believe both governments and individuals need to take responsibility. The government should enforce stricter environmental regulations and invest in cleaner energy sources. At the same time, individuals can help by using public transport, cycling, or walking whenever possible, instead of relying on private vehicles.

Overall, air pollution is a pressing issue in Vietnam, but with collective efforts, it can be reduced over time.
